-- Existential Introduction and Elimination (Sigma Types)
--
-- STATUS: CONCEPTUAL (Issue #114)
-- This file EXPLAINS how sigma types work in CredTT but does not demonstrate
-- actual sigma formation/elimination, which requires full dependent type support
-- in the checker. See credtt-impl/src/syntax.ml for the TSigma type constructor.
--
-- Classical: From P(a), derive exists x. P(x)
--            From exists x. P(x) and (forall x. P(x) -> Q), derive Q
-- CredTT: Credences multiply in both introduction and elimination
--
-- Example: There exists a prime greater than 100
-- Classical: Exhibit 101, done
-- CredTT: Witness credence * property credence

-- INTRODUCTION: (a, b) : Sigma x:A. B(x) @ c_a * c_b

-- Witness at credence c1
postulate witness : prime_101 @ c1

-- Property holds at credence c2
postulate property : greater_than_100 @ c2

-- Existential intro: credences multiply
-- (witness, property) @ c1 * c2

-- Why multiplication?
-- P(exists x. P(x)) = P(witness exists AND property holds)
-- Joint probability = product (assuming independence)

-- ELIMINATION: let (x, p) = e in body
-- If e : Sigma x:A. B @ c1 and body : C @ c2
-- Then result : C @ c1 * c2

-- Sigma at credence c
postulate sigma_term : exists_prime_gt_100 @ c

-- Elimination (using the witness) at credence d
postulate usage : using_the_prime @ d

-- Result: c * d
-- Each use of the existential MULTIPLIES credence

-- This is crucial for understanding existential reasoning:
-- Classical: "there exists" is definite
-- CredTT: "there exists @ c" tracks confidence

-- Low-credence existential:
-- "There probably exists a counterexample" @ 0.3
-- Using it in proof: 0.3 * (other credences)
-- The uncertainty propagates

-- High-credence existential:
-- "There definitely exists a witness" @ 1
-- Using it: 1 * d = d (no degradation)

-- Stability:
-- Stable witness * Stable property = Stable existential
-- Unstable anything = Unstable existential
